description.text:
print with support!

This is an upgrade for the E3D Titan Extruder.

Problems with current Titan design :

  • Filament insertion constantly missing the lower filament path in Direct Drive configuration
  • Flex/Nylon filaments sometimes gets kinked out because of no upper filament guide
  • PTFE path has little grip

How this solved the problem :

  • Longer grip for PTFE guide
  • upper filament guide
  • easier filament insertion
  • drop-in replacement

Printed in PLA. Use stronger/stiffer plastic if available.
I am pretty sure this would deform with time with PLA.

Happy Printing!

title: D-BOT Low Level Glass and Ally Heatbed With Silicone AC Heat Mat

description.text:
This is the 300mm x 300mm bed set up I'm currently using on my D-BOT.

I've used lower mounting points for the bed support springs which has gained about 10mm in build height. The bed consists of two laser cut alloy plates (3mm and 2mm respectively) which sandwich together a 6mm thick 300mm square cork mat from Amazon for insulation and a 300mm square silicone AC heat mat using M3 bolts.

On top of this sits a 3mm thick borosilicate glass plate, I know the argument with glass and ally beds but I'd already bought the glass on a whim so thought I might as well try it and see how it went, it would be possible to change the thickness of the top ally plate to 6mm and not bother with the glass at all, I may try this one day but this setup works perfectly for me at the moment. I'm able to print ABS with good results and the bed heats up to 120c in a couple of minutes.

The cables for the heater mat exit at the rear centre of the heat bed so I made a cable carrier to support them until they get to the cable chain that takes them down to the SSR, you'll also need to Earth both ally plates for safety's sake, use AC power wisely!!

All the printed parts are ABS, don't bother using PLA or PETG it will just melt if your going to use the bed at temperatures above 60c

I've included a .step file of the assembly for you to tinker around with.

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

solid

Notes:

Use ABS, PLA or PETG will melt or soften.

Persistence of Vision Spinner. Inspired by Tinkernut's, I decided to make my own.

I added a channel to run the wires for power through the spinner. I just paused my print the layer before they were covered up, ran the wires and then restarted. There are 3 small tabs on each side that hold the circuit board in place. If you use the same battery holder as I did it snaps right in. The side with LEDs and ATtiny however you have to use thin wire and clip all leads or solder on the back as flush as possible or it will sit too high to snap in with the tabs.

Code on my Github -> https://github.com/tkeeley/Arduino/blob/master/POV-Spinner.ino
*Thanks to Tinkernut for doing the leg work on this. I just modified his code so there was an option to put a space in the text.

comments.author: mcmasterp

comments.text: Have you tried a continuity test yet from socket pin to led? Ground on the socket should be electrically connected to all led grounds and the ground on the battery pack.  +3v power should only be electrically connected to + on the socket and the battery pack. Each led + should be only electrically connected to its corresponding pin on the socket. Test for any shorts that may be causing it to act the way it is.Also, make sure the attiny is  in the socket in the correct orientation. I've used these little chips so many times and still plug them in backwards from time to time.
comments.author: mcmasterp

comments.text: continuity test was a good idea. all checked out. It turned out to be because I changed the letters to my daughters name but used all caps. with lower case all is well. thank you again, I'll post a make as soon as glue dries

comments.author: mcmasterp

comments.text:
Pin 0 of the Attiny goes to the top led ( top of the letter ) to pin 4 of the Attiny85 to the bottom led (bottom of the letter). If you're not familiar with the pinout of the Attiny85 there are tons of diagrams online. A quick google search will bring up plenty.
pin 0 = top led
pin 1 = next led
pin 2 = next led
pin 3 = next led
pin 4 = bottom led

comments.text: A few tips before you dive in. Soldering the side with the leds and attiny85 was a pain. I matched the size and shape of the battery clip breakout on a piece of circuit board for symmetry and balance and it left very little room to work. I ran a bare wire down the negative side of the leds to connect them then connected led ground and batter ground to the attiny85 ground pin. I stripped phone wire to use fprbthe leds to attiny85 because it was the thinnest I had on hand. And I paused the printer just before the wire tunnels closed up to run a longer than needed wire through the spinner to connect power to the two sides. I just taped them in the opening with painters tape to keep them from getting caught up in the printer nozzle. But the biggest thing is just lay out the circuit board with the leds and attine85 before soldering so you can plan the placement. It's pretty crammed in there. And then if it does sit a little too high for the clips to hold it down, a dab of hot glue will take care of it. Good luck and post pics when it's done!!!

author: anagono

description.text:
Voron upgrades to 12mm Y rods to reduce deflection for larger builds. Since the Y rods don't move enlarging them has little downside. There are versions floating around that also enlarge the X rod but that greatly increases the amount of moving mass.

You do lose a few mm of X and Y due to the larger bearing size (my frame is oversized so I don't have an exact amount, should be about the difference between an LM8LUU and an LM12LUU).

BOM changes:
The Y shaft retainer screws become 4mm longer (4x m3 20mm).
2x LM8LUU -> 2x LM12LUU
2x 8mm shaft -> 2x 12mm shaft

V075 was retrofit and is currently using this modification.

Printing:
same as the rest of Voron 1.5 xy. 4 Perimeters, 5 top/bottom. 0.2 layer height, 0.4 nozzle.

Known issues:
The B idler assembly is a mirror of the A which flips the position of the upper and lower belt. Looks less symmetric but does not affect function. Will fix eventually.

The thicker bearing retainers have little clearance to the Z shaft support. Works fine on my build but might need a speck of plastic

The screw added to the rod retainer is untested and the hole in the motor mount will likely need to be enlarged. It is intended to allow minor adjustments to the rod position as the heavier rods are slightly harder to adjust. I found the added leverage from the plastic was sufficient.

F360 files provided. Where a B part was not provided it is a mirror of the A part.

description.text:
I did a close approximation of the origional , some of the bevels are different, but its basically the same thing. Included my source files.
I still dont know if its what I want, but atleast now I can print it!

I started this to be able to support all the wiring and at the same time be able to easily change wires.
I wanted the chain the other way around. ;-)
And used happily the original and Open Cable Chain Bidirectional
by tehmaze https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1556918 in it too.
And those beautiful springs, of course.

The Chainsupport is placed around a M5 bolt or on a M5 threaded rod or something like that and turns freely around it.
The Chainmount is meant for use with V-slots, as seen in picture.

A disadvantage of this thing is that it tends to shake sideways a bit. Pulling it very lightly upwards with a rubber band dampens that sufficiently.

It is indeed easy to remove/add wires, but even now I am still in doubt whether this is an improvement on the simple spiral wrap tube. It is not a big load on the moving carriage but the whole bunch wrapped up could also use a little support (perhaps the same rubber band ;-) ).
Please give me your thoughts. Thanks.

I use swapable hotends and was looking for a way to quicky connect my bowden tubes to the hotend. I couldn´t find anything so I created something myself.

My design uses four 5x3mm round magnets (like https://es.aliexpress.com/item/100pcs-Free-Shipping-Disc-Mini-5x3mm-N50-Rare-Earth-Strong-Neodymium-Magnet-Bulk-Super-Magnets-N50/2017438552.html) that holds and aligns the two parts, you can do without as normally the filament will prevent the two parts from sliding out. however it´s convenient when loading/changing the filament.

The pneumatic fittings are of the 4.3mm bore type (the ptfe tube can travel thru the fitting)
like: https://es.aliexpress.com/item/10-Pcs-Pneumatic-Fittings-PC4-M6-Bore-4-3mm-For-4mm-PTFE-Tube-connector-Coupler-Feed/32579949776.html?spm=2114.13010608.0.0.pvK4cl

assemble:
press magnets into holes (make sure that the are oriented all the same so they will not repel each other)
Insert the ptfe tube thru the fitting, screw the fitting in the part. push the tube so it just exists the printed part, cut off flush with the surface. On the small part you can shape the end in a funnel ( or V) shape a bit for easy filament loading

Usage:
loading: slide the two parts together, insert filament as usual
unloading: Remove filament (at least as far as it has cleared the parts), slide the parts to separate.

I liked and actually printed the original one but some bad wiring blew the fuse to the one I had and I can't find a fuse to replace it.
So found this switch at Lowes for about $6 and liked the way it looked. I will need to lower the hole ~5mm because the placement of it now is too high & the wiring behind it seems "smashed" up against the other wires which I'm not comfortable with.
Great design & I like the heat slots on it.
Switch: https://www.lowes.com/pd/SERVALITE-Double-Pole-Black-Light-Switch/50107270

Update: v2a is the same as v1 except the switch hold is lowered a little bit. I'll print that out & get pictures of it probably tonight.

Update #2: I just remembered I had to cut a little of the hole out with a knife to get the switch in. I apologize. I just uploaded a v1a and v2a that have cutout holes that are about 2mm bigger which should accommodate the switch correctly.

Update #3: I printed out the new STL file & the switch slid in & snapped very easily. As you can see from the pictures it's a bit lower as I mentioned before so as to not be pressed up against the wire box. Works great!!

This filament dryer is based on a widely available food dehydrator ECG SO 375. There are just a few added 3D printed parts. The construction is quite clear from the pohotos. All you have to do is mechanically remove the floors grids of each sections of the plastic container. Then connecte all the sections together (using "držák_obvodu.stl" part). I made it from PLA but it seems ABS or PET would be better choice because of maxium temperature which is up to 70 °C.

Requiry material:

1) Axial bearing 51106 (Internal diameter = 30 mm, external diameter = 47 mm, height is not cricial).
2) M3x16 + nuts + washers
3) M4x16 + nuts + washers

Have fun: it works really good! I mainly use it for ABS coils.

description.text:
This press was created since I was not able to find a perfectly working press which allows me to really easy remove a perfectly formed patty.
In my opinion there is only one suitable way to do it: After pressing the patty simply remove the press and the mold and the patty remains on your cutting board.
I suggest to press all patties side by side and put them together with the cutting board into the freezer for at least 1 hour.

To get already packed, perfectly formed, patties:

  1. Cover the mold with a sheet of wrapping film.
  2. Insert the meat.
  3. Cover the mold with another wrapping film.
  4. Press the patty.
  5. Bend the borders of the wrapping film into the mold.
  6. Press the patty again.
  7. Remove the Press and the mold.

If needed glue the "Press_Modification" part together with the Press. It allows to automatically form a dimple in the middle of the patty.
For me the base version without modification is working perfectly.

author: shivinteger

description.text:
Made a simple foldable range extender for the Dji Mavic PRO, without any silly nametags as everyone else only the best name, Dji Mavic PRO ;)!

Fits the spark controller aswell, even though it says DJI mavic PRO hehe.

I used aluminium tape that is used for ventilation, works as a charm!

The mounting holes for the antennas might change as they have no sort of support.
but if it works just fine anywayys i'll lieave it as is :)

I printed them standing up and with support, not as in the stl files so you have to orient them so the base with the antenna hole is down when printing :)!

comments.text: Nice job, think this will fit the Spark controller as well?  Thanks

comments.text:

Dont know the spark but if it is the same size antennas and the same measurement betweend them it should :)!

description.text:
Jousting Dragon knights:
Remember the video game 'Joust' or the movie Labyrinth? - I designed my own #ChipERemix to joust dragon riding knights.

  • Used void spaces to fit and hold ChipE parts while allowing for wiring.
  • This design only uses the 26 screws for the hip and ankle servo 'horn and idlers'.
  • The tip of the tail can pop off to plug in and recharge the battery.
  • The LCD is reforged as a shield.

Enjoy a Renaissance Faire with these protectors at your side, tilt at windmills, or settle an argument the old fashioned way!

Thanks to:
solidt for some knight
falken76 for some beasty
ljbotero for some scaly samples
Thingiverse and makerbot (2x)
and RobotGeek! #ChipERemix

Notes:

The ankle armor needs to be shrunk vertically about 25% to allow for flexibility of movement.

Used 'Zap a Gap' for model assembly.
Used small file for IR sensor space, rounding feet C bracket slots, as well as a little of the tail to accommodate battery and wires. Used Spray paint to color and metallic sharpies for detailing before assembly. If tip of tail is too loose, wrap a rubber band tightly around the power connector to the battery for friction fit. Can even use Velcro to attach knight and head to body for board reprogramming; a better way is to add a 90 degree micro USB extension cable instead (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00W6URQPE) tucked in the back.

Solenoids mounted at 90 degrees though I have them 'rest' forward.
I added spare rubber pads to the talons.

Followed RobotGeek ChipE instructions for wiring and some assembly.
https://www.robotgeek.com/robotgeek-chip-e.aspx
http://learn.robotgeek.com/projects/297-chip-e-assembly-guide.html

DragonRider Video

description.text:
This is a re-mix of my Simple RAMPS 1.4 mount to be compatible with the new Re-Arm Smoothieboard. This mount is beefed up from the original RAMPS 1.4 mount to fix some of the original breaking issues I had.

Simple mount that holds a RAMPS 1.4, Re-Arm Smoothieboard, and cooling fans. Slots in side of "case" allow for neat running of stepper motor and other wires to keep them out of the airflow path. The fan mount is designed to allow the use of several different fan options depending upon what you have on hand.

There are also two different fan mounts- one short and one tall depending upon how much room you need for wires and how much room there is available in your printer.

Mounting holes are sized for M5 allow for attachment to 80-20 extrusions, or whatever else you'd like.

Drill and tap fan mount holes for M3. Drill and tap holes in base for whatever size screws you prefer to mount the Smoothieboard.

I've included the Solidworks files for remixing.

title: Whisper foiling catamaran adjustable rudder holder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
In shallow waters one needs to keep the rudder in a middle position. This is an adjustable strap that can be quickly set and removed. When applying two of those print parts one can have two heights pre-adjusted.

The 3D printed "twister" has 3 holes to tightly fit a 3mm rope. You run the rope zig-zag through those three holes to achieve enough friction. Remember that friction is higher when there is rope tension on both sides of the twister.

At the lower end i used a 5mm bungee that is simply pulled over the T foil at the rudder. The bungee should provide enough tension so that the rope doesnt slide in the twister.

title: MINECRAFT PINS!
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
These are Minecraft pins you can use to hang things and decorate your walls! Enjoy!

These use pins from normal plastic thumbtacks, carefully smash or heat the plastic part to extract the small tack.

There are 3 ways to print these:
-SIMPLE: print with the pin slot facing upwards and place the pin in after with superglue.
-HALF: print with the pin slot facing upwards and glue the 2 halves together encasing the pin.
-EMBEDDED: use your slicer to determine the last layer that you can pause the print and place the pins embedding the pins cleanly. (this method is shown in the video)

Design/print/paint timelapse video: https://youtu.be/4t6ze6BNeDg

This is a microphone holder for a Traps E500 drum kit with the 5-spoke design. It replaces the electronic pickup module that is attached to the centre of the drum with 3 screws. It works really well if you replace the mesh heads on the kit with acoustic drum heads, and will hold an SM57-style microphone in place under the drum. There are 2 versions of the holder in here, a tested and working version 1.0, and an untested version 2.0 which increases the strength and flexibility of the microphone mount, along with a slightly larger microphone diameter.

Meant to be tapped with M6, can also be found on my hypercube Evolution Parts thing. I thought about making a space for the hammer nut to fit, however that would leave only 2mm of plastic holding, so I actually think that that assembly would be much weaker. Your should probably consider this more cosmetic than structural

title: ESP8266 Door Contact Housing
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Housing for low power MQTT wifi contact based on Arduino Mini Pro and ESP8266.
Bit ugly again, but easy to print.
Both processor boards, reed-contact, step-up-converter and two AAA are fitting in the housing.

With white PLA the flashing status LED of Mini and ESP can be seen through the housing.

The software/electronic part took me muuuuch longer then expected.
But now it runs on some µA in standby.
Dropped the easy Code for Arduino, too. ESP is running via EasyESP. (Contact and Batt-Status).
Will upload a sketch of the circuit diagram as well. May I draw it in CAD. We will see.

Be aware that I used a reed-contact for real alarm systems. So it's N/C not N/O.

UPDATE 2.Sep.2017: schematic is uploaded as picture.

P.S. Lid is still a bit lose. But for the first shoot okay.

UPDATE, 3.Nov.2017:
First Batteries are empty now. My Step-Up-Converter stopped working at 2.45V.
I didn't implemented the persistence on openhab right away.
But to give you a first idea, I uploaded a diagram of the battery discharge.
May be you want to extrapolate by yourself.
(A quick calc brought me to approximately 120 days for a two persons with a normal job)

description.text:
Designed in tinkercad, purposed to be able to stack several together.
Driven by a single source, but able to individually couple each or any of them to the driive, with an additional reduction of 5:1.
Added mounting holes for 8mm shafts. It might need some spacers in practice.

The concept is to add some cheap lock actuators to engage the gear to the drive, and a spring to keep them uncoupled when non-energized.

I've included in the files a key to join the gear with the head, and a "tool" to help mounting the shafts, measured 41.5mm apart (not intentional :p)

That's all for now.

description.text:
I designed this for someone who is into making Egg in the Basket (I grew up calling it Toad in the Hole) - an egg fried into a circular hole cut in a slice of bread, so the bread soaks up the egg yolk. She wanted the perfect size cutter; I wanted to make it easy to use and comfortable on the hands.

The sine-wave grip in the center is nice to hold while you're twisting, and the faceted circle seems nice for cutting through the bread.

The circular cookie cutter is possibly the easiest useful object to design... but I thought my variation might be useful.

title: Adjustable Y Axis Linear Bushing / Mount

description.text:
This is an adjustable linear bushing with mount, for a Prusa I3 Y axis. Also depending on the style of frame used for your 3D printer there may be clearance issues.

This type of bushing helps with differences in printing tolerances by allowing one half to flex. The screw holes help hold the flexible half in position with the added benefit to adjust for wear.

Hole spacing 30mm
Adjustment screws are M3 - i recommend using grub screws if you have them.
Note: Needs to be printed at 0.2 mm layer height with a 0.4 mm nozzle.

This is a replacement support for a drawer rail in our motorhome.  It seems like I need to replace one of these every year, so I thought I'd make one out of ABS and see if it holds up any better.
Edit:
The original version of this was slightly off in one dimension, so I re-sized it and added the new files with "_corrected" on the end.

If your motorhome is similar to mine, the STL file might work for you.  Just print and go.  If not, I provided the SCAD file so you can modify it to suit you.  Sorry, it's not commented at all, but it isn't too big, so you can probably figure it out yourself.  The toughest part was getting the inlet of the slot to taper for ease of use.

title: Jeep Wrangler JK Roll Bar S Gear Hook for Padded Rear Horizontal Bar

description.text:
I previously made a J hook for metal detectors for the vertical part of the roll bar. They've been working great. https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2355327

I used some bungees for hanging stuff from the horizontal top bar but it was difficult to hook and unhook items. After a series of 3 creation failures (PETG is very flexible) I ended up incorporating hook loop strips into this solution and is now working fine for getting items off the floor (more dog room). Easy to hook a strap for travel and unhook for use without needing a full reach in to manipulate both the hook and handle.

The canvas bag pictured is quite heavy. It destroyed the first version and didn't last long with a double thick version but so far so good with this thicker wider velcro strapped snug version. The little V plug helps keep the hook & loop straps securely mounted in the S-Hook body.

I used 3/4" double sided velcro/hook & loop strapping (~20mm). The V holds in place best if the rough/loop side of the strap is in contact with the V surfaces e.g. smoother side out. Once snugged into place for awhile the V plugs hold the strap in place for repeated open/close efforts.

title: Honeycomb Cable Organizer
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Honeycomb Cable Organizer

A customizable cable organizer that can configure arbitrary number and set of hexagon containers together, with differing heights.

Uses

  • Cable organizer
  • Tool holder
  • Desktop Pen Organizer
  • Basis for other honeycomb projects

Description

Specify the size of a hex side, as well as your wall width. The cutout at the bottom is useful for cables if you need to push something through. For other cases, like a tool holder, this may be 0 so the bottom is 'wall' width.

To decide how many cells, you must specify an array of arrays, which is a little complicated. For those of you not familiar with programming, the easiest way to think of this is a grid. So laying out each inner array on it's own line is like the rows of a grid. Play around with a couple of configurations and I'm sure you'll get it.

I'm NOT certain how the online customizer tools will configure this so YMMV.

Origin Story

After my last trip, I was cranky that my cables were such a mess, even though I put them in a plastic bag and wrap each one individually. I was inspired by some of the existing honeycomb designs, but none of them were customizable. So, my to my significant other's chagrin, I spent a Sunday putting this together. It's always fun to work on geometry and remember my trig.

description.text:
Customizable Drawer

A scad file that can create:

  • Drawer - can customize horizontal and vertical spacers, configure HxWxD
  • Drawer holder - to fit drawers
  • Drawer holder extension - to support double-height drawers in a stack
  • Lid - to cover a stack of drawers
  • Connector - BUGBUG: not working yet

Caveat Emptor

I've printed a bunch of these for my own use. The drawer, and holder work well. I've glued them together thus far. Was thinking of making a snap connector to click them together, but not done implementing/testing it yet.

Customizing

Most everything in it is customizable. This makes it great to fit to your printer, or your particular needs. How many spacers you want is super helpful. Further, it is made to create multiple STL files with openscad on the command line. It allows you to pick what kind of STL to output by specifying the mode.

title: GoPro style mount for Arducam 5MP Raspberry Pi camera module

description.text:
This design is intended to be compatible with boards that have mounts for larger lens on them like the Arducam 5 Megapixels 1080p OV5647 Camera Module with CS Mount Lens (that I have). The board must measure less than 36mm and have mounting holes 29mm square.

For the three prong version the hex opening may be slightly undersized for some bolts. I pushed into place with a soldering iron on the bolt head to get a perfect fit. The ones I've printed work well with the injection molded accessories my knock-off action camera came with but most printable extension arms on here are a difficult fit and require some sanding to get the fit right.

Autodesk Fusion 360 links:
2 prong - http://a360.co/2tEw2Gt
3 prong - http://a360.co/2t7qemE
3 w/ mount side cable slot - http://a360.co/2tBZu13
2 w/ mount side cable slot - http://a360.co/2sJTela

Printer:

Creality CR-10

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

Simplify3D put in supports for the bolt hole in the GoPro mount bracket. Some printers may be able to bridge that without distorting the opening too much. I just let the slicer do it's thing and printed the supports. They may not be necessary.

I printed .2 height 4 layers top, bottom, side with 30% infill. Probably overkill for most use cases but mine is bolted to an arm attached to the traveling print bed.

To stress relief the ribbon cable, feed the flat cable through one of the loops and plug into the board before you screw the board down to the mount.

I used 4 M4 socket head cap screws to secure the board by screwing the threads directly into the plastic. You could use M3 hardware with nuts on the back if you like.

comments.text: Love the design, I went to print it and it looked too big. So I opened up the Fusion 360 links, and measured the hole centers.  Sure enough, Fusion states the hole centers are 29mm in this model, Raspberry PI spec's for the camera are 21mm for hole centers.  Am I missing something really stupid?
comments.author: phucknob

comments.text: So I did some research and as I suspected there are many revision to the Rasp Pi camera. The one I modeled this for, using actual caliper measurements of the one in my hand was a 5mp Arducam variant. I didn't realize it was a different dimension than the standard RasPi module. I'll need to change the title to reflect that.

description.text:
Got tired of fishing out plastic, dusk, and who knows what else in the open slots of my V-Slot. This is an attempt to solve the problem. While not as seamless as the product offered in the OpenBuilds part store - it does have some advantages.

  1. you can customize the length without any waste.
  2. you can customize the color

*** Mark 3 has some improvements that will allow these to be slightly inset to the surrounding V-Slot face.

Supports:

No

Infill:

25%

Notes:

Use only with flexible material - I used NinjaFlex and MakerGeek's MakerFlex. I don't recommend you go over 30% infill on this - otherwise you'll having to hammer in the printed parts. The tolerances are tight - so make sure your printer is well tuned. The default length is 20mm, however, you can clearly adjust it with your slicer easily enough.

I printed mine with the widest portion on the bed - effectively upside down from how it will be inserted into the slot.

print_settings.Notes:: Also, a lower temperature makes it less lossy over the bed. I used 180 deg.

description.text:
DISCLAIMER:
I DID NOT CREATE THIS MODEL. THE TALENTED ARTISTS AT AVALANCHE SOFTWARE DID. I TAKE ABSOLUTELY NO CREDIT FOR THIS WORK. PROPERTY OF DISNEY INTERACTIVE STUDIOS (CURRENTLY OWNED BY WARNER BROS. INTERACTIVE ENTERTAINMENT SINCE EARLY 2017). USED WITHOUT PERMISSION.

-ripped from disney infinity 3
-edited in blender
-removed nothing
-kept everything

i wanted to try a model w/ a lot of sharp edges, so hulkbuster was an ideal candidate.

after marking sharps and creases for the last few hours i'm exhausted, but i did learn a lot and my workflow is improving. there are some minor issues w/ his back, and his high arches might be problematic for printing the first layer (maybe try to print rafts). otherwise i left him intact and didn't even remodel manifold edges, leaving that task to netfabb instead. hopefully the model's ok. i sliced him up and scanned through the layers but haven't printed him yet so do it at your own risk. the shoulder pads hover and i didn't want to extrude/booleans them into the body, so supports are a definitely a must. i kept the edges as sharp as possible since they'll be dulled down anyway by printing layers.

this model was subsurface modified at 2x (~11MB) but i can send you a 3x (40MB+) if you really want to print this at a larger size. let me know if you have any questions, issues or recommendations.

Notes:

this is a pretty complex model. i really shouldn't be telling you how to use your printer.
knob to replace for a 6 position TS performance chip tuner, may fit other standard potentiometer style D shaped shafts. will fit a shaft of diameter 6.3mm and 5.4mm dia flat.

description.text:
Conic spiral guide spool. (For lack of a better description.)

This might have use for pull-string applications where you want a bit more torque to get things moving, but more speed at the end. Little guide lip of the spiral shape keeps the string from sliding down the cone as it's pulled.

Of course there may be other uses, but that is one I can think of.

Added a second variant, based on the "Extra objects addon" logarithmic spiral. Modeled a bit different than the first one, but serving a similar purpose.

This adapter is designed to attach a DSLR to a telescope. There is a slight taper at the end to allow a snug fit. The adapter prints pretty well but I found the supports that were generated in Slic3r to be difficult to remove. description.text: This is a battery holder to deliver 7-8 V by linking 5 AA batteries in series. There is also a bracket that can be used to hold the batteries in a project.

Notes:

In addition to the battery holder a bracket is provided that can be permanently attached to a project. The battery holder can be removed from the holder so that the batteries can be changed. The holder snaps into the bracket.

Assembly

ABS was used. Two parts are glued together to form one piece. A tab in each section ensures the polarity is aligned properly.
Four 1/4"x1-5/8"xx0.016" brass bars are used to connect the batteries. The thin bars slide into slots at the ends of the battery holder then bent in to form contacts for the batteries.
Two small brass bolts (#4-40 x 3/8") serve as terminals to which wires can be connected with nuts or soldered. Polarity of the batteries are marked on the ends of the holder.

description.text: This is a Voronoi-like pen holder. I say Voronoi-like, because I'm not convinced its an actual Voronoi diagram. I generated the mesh by creating a sort of twisted square-based cylinder in Blender and then used Meshmixer's dual graph pattern to generate the mesh. While the Voronoi diagram is the dual graph of a Delaunay triangulation, I suspect this is simply the dual of the original triangulation produced in Blender, which is almost certainly not Delaunay.

Notes:
  • 0.2 mm layer height for strength and fidelity to fillets
  • 40% infill - lighter infills may work but I haven't tried (start with 40% and work down)
  • PLA for stiffness - PETG's flex makes for a rubbery opening experience

There is a 20 mm bridge for the penny slot - don't be discouraged! If you're using Slic3r, take a look at the Bridge Flow Ratio setting in the Advanced section of Print Settings. This is a ratio by which the printer will under-extrude during bridging which will effectively stretch the filament over the bridged section. The first bridge layer will be thinner but straighter as a result. I'm using 0.9 currently with good results.

Don't be discouraged if you see some sagging in the penny slot bridge; trim it out and you'll likely find that you can jam a penny in there regardless. If not, what better time than now to figure out your bridge problems? There will be drinks when you're done!
Iterative process of four different revisions. I'm not sure anyone cares to know more but let me know if details sound interesting.

This set contains 2 magic circle floor tiles, and those same floor tiles half surrounded by a circular wall. This was created for my Rise of the Runelords campaign, specifically for Skull Crossing in the module The Hook Mountain Massacre. These tiles are designed to fit with the Smooth Edge Tile Series.
The full scene picture uses a mix of OpenForge tiles and Dwarven Forge tiles.
OpenForge floor tiles are designed to be compatible with Dwarven Forge dungeon tiles. Compatible tiles/walls in this series are tagged with OpenForge
You can find this set on github

  • Smooth Tile Series - Smooth tiles that can be used as concrete, dirt, ice, etc.

print_settings.Notes:: I would recommend experimenting printing the legs first, increasing the scale until they look nice and strong (that was around 300% for my anet A8) and printing the entire thing at that scale. I noticed when slicing the legs the upper curved stick on the front two legs was not fully attached so the leg files ending in "joint" are reinforced. The original legs are also not capable of supporting the weight of the model so I strengthened the thinnest part of the legs and saved them ending in "wide" i would recommend using these legs rather than the original or joint reinforced files. I also noticed when slicing the eye hole was too deep making holes on either side through to the slots for the arms. The body file ending in fixed has a slightly less shallow hole making it slice properly. The antenna also tends to not print well so I have attached the file separately so you can print them out and attach them separately if they do not print well initially. Attach the arms by pushing one arm shaft all the way through the body and then gluing the other arm shaft directly onto the other, this allows the arms to still be rotated up and down and positioned while still being securely attached. Hope this helps. Good Luck.

It doesn't really matter though, use what gives you the best results with your printer.  Unless you have particularly thick walls, the infill only applies to the base of the shoulder, so adjust as necessary to make it strong enough to hold your eye bolt and stand up to your ejection force.

description.text:
Stuphi made a lovely nose cone scad model that generates the basic nose cone shape. What this scad file does is wraps that nose cone library with some utility functions to control wall thickness, shoulder size, and a hole to mount an eye bolt to. I've successfully used this to make a variety of nose cones. Pictured are two different sizes that fit a standard paper roll tube, and a replacement nose cone for the Estes Flutter By.

To get the required nose cone shape library, visit one the following URLs:

  • https://github.com/stuphi/NoseCone
  • https://www.youmagine.com/stuphi/designs

Note that some adhesives don't work well with printed plastics, so be sure your shoulder piece is well-secured to the nose cone. The ridges from the layers actually help here since it provides space foe the adhesive to lock in place.

Also, be sure you get good layer adhesion. There's not a lot of sheering force on the nose, but you wouldn't want it coming part in flight.

In most cases, you'll want to secure an eyebolt to the shoulder using a fastening method that will never come loose (epoxy on the nut on the inside is one way), and then glue the shoulder into the nose cone (add weight first if necessary).

Unless you have particularly thick walls, the infill only applies to the base of the shoulder, so adjust as necessary to make it strong enough to hold your eye bolt and stand up to your ejection force.

title: Dyson V8 accessory mounting bracket (Updated - V1_1)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Minor Update - V1_1 (13/3/18) Removed the countersink chamfers from the screw holes to reduce the risk of a splitting the model when mounting. Use a pan head or machine head type of screw. Also, changed the orientation so the stl places it in the correct (well, at least as I like to print it) orientation on the bed when slicing. Of course, you are welcome to place any way you would prefer ;) .

The Dyson V8 comes with 6 fittings (7 if you count the pipe) but only 2 places to hang them. My broom closet is rather small so I needed a way of mounting where I could choose the placement for each fitting. The mount has been designed so that the Dyson fittings hang from it.

Notes:

Refer to the second photo see the suggested print orientation. The supports breaks out easily. Minor cleanup required but Dyson parts will fit directly as it comes from the 3d printer. I included the gcode (V1_0) if you trust the way I sliced it ;) and are printing with PLA. Otherwise, use the stl and slice it yourself.

Minor cleanup and removal of the supports. Best way to mount is to pilot drill a single hole to start and then screw the bottom of the bracket onto the wall. This will allow you to rotate till level and then pilot drill the top 2 holes and fix with appropriate screws.

I used particle board screws and had to drill the holes out slightly so the screw thread would not bite into the plastic. Also, use a hand screwdriver as the countersunk shape of the screws apply huge force and will split the plastic if you are not careful. You could print it with 95-100% infill to make it stronger but I think the part is strong enough for the task at 40%, just be careful when fixing it on the wall.

author: Duke_S

description.text:
UPDATED 10 September 2014: New documentation file documentation-with-oshpark-links.html which has OSH Park links for ordering circuit boards. Removed old batchpcb.com links as batchpcb.com was sold to OSH Park. Use this file in place of the index.html file in the dice.zip file. This project provides four sets of plans (schematics, board layouts, etc.) for Arduino and AVR based, animated digital dice. Also included are 3D models for printing enclosures for two of the smaller designs.
A (very non-exciting) video of the dice in action may be seen at http://youtu.be/Kp_W-V4TNko .
The files dice.zip and dice.tar.gz provide the full documentation, source code, .hex files, Eagle CAD files, Gerber files for use with a fab, OpenSCAD enclosure models, rendered .stl files, etc. for the projects. See the index.html file in the distribution for the documentation. These materials are being distributed under the TAPR Open Hardware License, http://tapr.org/OHL .
The projects demonstrate using the following AVR and Arduino features
  • button debouncing,
  • sleeping the device using power down mode,
  • awakening the device from sleep with a change to a low voltage state on the INT0 pin,
  • enabling and disabling the watchdog timer interrupt,
  • software PWM using a timer/counter compare interrupt, and
  • implementing simple (i.e., non-precise) timed delay functions.
    The necessary hardware is straightforward, requiring
  • a microcontroller with at least eight digital I/O pins,
  • seven LEDs,
  • seven current limiting resistors for the seven LEDs,
  • a momentary push button switch,
  • a pull-up resistor for use with the push button switch,
  • an optional bypass capacitor for the microcontroller, and
  • a power source such as a 3V coin cell or two AAA batteries for use with an AVR microprocessor.
    C language source code for AVR-GCC is provided which has been tested on an Arduino Duemilanove (ATmega328p), an ATtiny24, and an ATtiny2313. The same source code file works for all three processors and can be used as an Arduino sketch.
    While the projects are intended for an Arduino, ATtiny24/44/84, or ATtiny2313/4313, the sources can be built for other processors (but may need changes). The documentation also includes links for ordering individual boards from oshpark.com starting at $10.95 for
    three of the small boards (OSH Park sells in units of three just like Ramans, http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rendezvous_with_Rama).

For complete instructions, see the index.html file in the dice.zip or dice.tar.gz files. Those two archives have identical contents.
For printing just the enclosures,
  • Each part -- enclosure lid, enclosure bottom -- is in a separate .STL file. No reason why you cannot print them both at the same time. That's just the way I did them.
  • The dimensions of the parts favor a 0.3 mm slicing height, but use whatever works best for you.
  • The "slop" between the lid's gutter and the bottom's lip is loose: I did that intentionally for folks with printers calibrated differently. You can make it less loose if you want by tweaking the OpenSCAD sources. However, once the enclosures are screwed shut, it won't make any difference.
  • Slice the parts with 100% infill and 3 or 4 shells. Use of extra shells may help prevent issues with the cylindrical posts not having fill between their inner and outer walls.
  • Print them with or without rafts: I printed them without.
    5a. Screws needed for the medium sized enclosure: four #1 self tapping screws 5/16 - 3/8 inches long (1.4 - 1.5 mm self tapping screws, 8 - 10 mm long).
    5b. Screws needed for the small sized enclosure: two #0 self tapping screws, 5/16 - 3/8 inches long (1.4 - 1.5 mm self tapping screws 8 - 10 mm long).

title: CB adapter for wanhao duplicator and clones.

description.text:
Well I thought I did not need to edit this thing, however I was wrong. You can actually fit the fan inside of the control box as well. I may do a video covering this on its own. most of the insulation is the same as the method I already listed. So if you want to push or suck air, you can do both.

This is a small and simple adapter made to attach a 75X75X30 blowerfan to the control box of the wanhao duplicator and it's various clones. To my knowledge they have not changed the box on the clones or the new 2.1 printers. I know the plus removes the box entirely.
I have done a 12 hour print test with the new fan installed, along with smaller prints. I can feel a slight bit of air flow through the holes on the side of the box, however it's pretty faint.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

12

Notes:

This took around 50 minuets for me to print

Hardware

While this mod does reuse hardware in the printer, it does need a few bits of hardware.

  1. A 75X75X30mm blower fan ( This is the fan I am using in the picture, it also arrived with two screws and nuts as well. https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B016UCKBUA/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o06_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1 )

  2. A M4 nut and M4 screw 40mm length should be long enough. My fan came with two screws and nuts.

Install steps with pictures

  1. Remove back of control box

  2. Remove stock fan from control box

  3. Run wire of new fan through the mount and original air holes.

  4. Wire fan up to to printer.

  5. Close control box up.

  6. Use the screws holding the stock fan to mount the adapter to the back of the control box.

  7. Install fan into adaptor (be sure to run fan wire through one of the two mount screw openings

  8. Use one M4 screw and nut to secure fan to mount to ensure it stays attached to printer.
Back of control box 40mm fan located inside of control box Fan wire ran through mount and back of control box. Back reattached to control box with fan wired up Mount attached to backplate Fan installed with fan wire running through indentation for mounting screws

For this Modified GRBL 1.1f CNC Control Firmware to work, you need to connect two stepper motors to X axis and Z axis on CNC Shield. Because my Arduino pin for Y direction is burned so I make it work on Z axis. Connect Servo Sense wire (Yellow) to Z- pin, Red to +5V pin and Black or Brown to GND pin on CNC Shield. I use Laser Web 4 to generate and send GCode to the machine. You need to change GCode Setting in this software. Go to Setting -> GCode -> and fill in "M3S55" for Tool On and "M3S0" for Tool Off. To connect to Auduino, make sure you select your Baudrate to 115200 under Comms Tab.

description.text: These are replacement parts for my iBlason cell phone holster. I was tired of buying a case every few months so I made parts. The rivet usually breaks or the clip hinge. I beefed up the hinge and added thickness also external spring. Improved the rivet with fillets. Try to print the rivet at 45 degrees in order to prevent weak points. I used a cotter pin for the hinge but later drilled it out and used a 2mm (or 3mm) bolt. The finish will vary based on your printer but I used acetone to help. I have used this for several months with no issues. Your mileage may vary so don't blame me if your phone comes off and gets broken because I feel these parts are way better made than the original. You may have to file the rivet a little depending on your print quality.

print_settings.Notes:: FilamentSensor1.1-lid-only.stl

title: Filament Sensor for Octoprint (Monoprice Select Mini)

description.text:
I was jealous that other 3D printer users had their own filament sensor accessories, and I thought it was about time for a Monoprice Select Mini user to have make it happen! So I ordered a Makerbot 1.2 style endstop from China^^, completed a 10 project course on Fusion 360 on Udemy, and waited 5 weeks for the endstop to arrive.

Now we have a working filament runout sensor which pauses your prints and waits for you to tell it to resume the print (ideally after you've installed a fresh roll of filament). ;)

Please look for the Supplies section below to see what parts you need to make sure you have ready to go before beginning this project. Under Post Printing you can find a brief guide for how to put these supplies together, and in particular how to setup Octoprint to pause your prints when the endstop indicates the filament is not longer present.

Printer:

Monoprice Select Mini

Resolution:

.2625

Infill:

20%

Notes:

FilamentSensor1.1.stl has both parts of this model nicely plated right next to each other in a way that I believe will help your mini print with less movement.

If you need to replace just one of the two parts, print FilamentSensor1.1-lid-only.stl or FilamentSensor1.1-bottom-only.stl.

Quick Setup Guide

Wiring a Raspberry Pi, installing, and configuring Octoprint is outside the scope of this guide. However, these are the tasks you will need to complete.

  1. Install the Filament Sensor Reloaded.
  2. Connect the endstop to the Raspberry Pi. (Might I suggest this printable to assist with this?) On the Raspberry Pi 3 the pins are:
    Pin 1: 3.3vdc
    Pin 6: Ground
    Pin 7: GPIO4
  3. Configure Filament Sensor Reloaded's settings:
    Pin: 7
    Debounce Time: 250 ms
    Switch Type: Normally Open
  4. Copy and paste the code from the Octoprint "GCODE Scripts" section below, into the "GCODE Scripts" section of Octoprint settings.
  5. Restart octoprint.^^^
Assembly Guide

After you have gathered your hardware, configured the software, and printed this case you are going to what to know where to put it. Well, I can help you out there.

Step 1

Remove these two screws, and set them somewhere safe. You will use them to hold the sensor case in place.

Figure 1 Step 2

Put the case in its place and secure it with the screws you removed in Step 1.

Figure 2a. Figure 2b. This screw is designed to go in before the endstop board is installed. Step 3

⚠ Note: This is going to be tight! ... and it was designed that way. I wanted to design an accessory that did not require any additional hardware to secure the board in place. Just be gentle when putting the switch arm in place and you will be alright.

Start with the board into the case the angle shown in Figure 3a below. Then with your fingers gently pressing on the white plug and closing the switch arm carefully lower the board into place until it is flat on the bottom and the switch arm is inside of the filament slot opening.

Figure 3a. Set the board at this angle to begin. Figure 3b. Using two hands here will make this much easier! Step 4

Plug your jumper wires into the board.

Figure 4. Use the cable that came with your endstop as a guide. For example, mine had red, black, and green wires (which are used for 3.3v, ground, and signal respectively). Step 5

Test the endstop with the board plugged into your Octoprint board. If the LED is ON before you insert the filament, the metal switch arm is caught on the case and needs to be adjusted.

⚠ Note: Even though these boards are based on an open source design, there are slight variances in size from each manufacturer. I have tried two different boards and they had a 0.1mm difference in dimension in the width and depth of the board.

By trying a combination of board placement adjustment and careful bending of the metal switch arm I was able to get both endstop boards to work correctly. Keep at it until the LED stays out when filament is absent from the case.

For proper functionality to occur the LED on the endstop should turn off when the filament is removed from the case. (You can test this easily by inserting then removing a piece of filament to make sure the adjustments you performed are working well.)

Step 6

Attach the handy snap-fit lid. Start with the back side of the case as shown in Figure 5 below, then click in the front side.

Congratulations!

If you have Octopi configured properly you should be able to insert some filament and get printing!

Figure 6. After the filament passes out the other side of the sensor, you should see the right side of the case glow red. This indicates the filament has been sensed.

Change Log
  • 7/23/2017 12pm PST
    Actually uploaded v1.1 STL files. Thanks for the heads up Mookiefer!
  • 7/22/2017 9:15pm PST
    1.1 Release! Tolerances were relaxed a bit to better accommodate an endstop made by DAOKI. I now have this endstop working on my personal Select Mini.
  • 7/16/2017 3pm PST
    1.0 Release! Major changes since Prototype: 1.) A snap-fit lid has been added to keep the board in place, 2.) Source Files.zip includes Fusion 360 archive format and a STEP file. 3.) a visual assembly guide!
  • 7/12/3017 10:00am PST
    Prototype 8: 1.) Removed seam where stabilizer model attaches to the case. 2.) Per the recommendation of Patrick Nixon I reduce the stabilizer arm width from 5.5mm to 4mm, and the screw surround from from ~11mm to 9mm. This should help fit around more extruder assemblies.
  • 7/11/2017 4:30pm PST
    Prototype 7: Improved the filament channel and blocked all escape routes. ;) Also tightened up the overall model. The endstop board fits quite snugly and may not even need a lid to keep it in place.
  • 7/10/2017 12:20pm PST
    First draft of instructional guide.
  • 7/10/2017 7:55am PST
    Prototype 5B: Added stabilizing arm with a second screw to keep the sensor from rotating.
FAQ

Question: Why did you choose this board when a plain switch would work?

Answer: Technically, we could use a switch, but I chose this board for three reasons. 1.) it's widely available, 2.) It is easy to plug in with female to female jumpers, 3.) It has an LED to provide instant feedback.

Question : I would like to create a remix. Will you share your source files?

Answer: *Download *Source Files.zip". I included a Fusion 360 archive file, as well as a STEP file.

To order (if you don't have these on hand)
  1. Makerbot 1.2 style endstop (open source design)^^^^
  2. Jumpers: Female to Female
You should already have these setup and working
  1. Monoprice Select Mini 3D Printer.
  2. A device with Octoprint installed on it. Might I suggest a Raspberry Pi 3 with Octopi installed?

After print job is paused 
M117 Print Paused

{% if pause_position.x is not none %}
; relative XYZE
G91
M83

; retract filament, move Z slightly upwards
G1 Z+5 E-5 F4500 

; absolute XYZE
M82
G90

; move to a safe rest position, adjust as necessary
G1 X0 Y100
{% endif %}
Before print job is resumed 
M117 Print Resumed

{% if pause_position.x is not none %}
; relative extruder
M83

; prime nozzle
G1 E-5 F4500
G1 E5 F4500
G1 E5 F4500

; absolute E
M82

; absolute XYZ
G90

; reset E
G92 E{{ pause_position.e }}

; move back to pause position XYZ
G1 X{{ pause_position.x }} Y{{ pause_position.y }} Z{{ pause_position.z }} F4500

; reset to feed rate before pause if available
{% if pause_position.f is not none %}G1 F{{ pause_position.f }}{% endif %}
{% endif %}

^ I uploaded this early prototype per the request of Derek Were-Yeti Mitchell on the wonderfully supportive MP Select Mini Owners Facebook Group.

^^ Or you can get and endstop much quicker from Amazon (for example: this one).

^^^ Choose "Restart System" on the Power menu on the Octoprint web interface.

^^^^ Make sure the one you order looks like the one in the photos. Do not order one with a roller as it won't fit.

title: Filament Spool Holder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
3D printer filament spool holder

  • It's very simple but sturdy.
  • It works with almost any 1kg or less filament spools on the market.
  • It doesn't require bearings.

Happy printing!

Printer:

TEVO Tarantula

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm(layer), 0.5mm(width)

Infill:

20%

Notes:

This spool holder is made up of 6 parts:

  • Filament Spool_base x 4
  • Filament Spool_wall x 2
  • When assembling those parts, use a rubber or plastic hammer to fit them tight.

At the top of spool holder, there is a hole in hexagonal shape.

  • Use a pencil or a ball pen to uphold the spool.
  • Most of hexagonal pencils such as a Dixon will fit in the hold nicely.
  • Round pencils will have no problem as well.

Design parameters:
Spool's OD: 200mm
Spool's ID: 52mm
Spool's Width: 70mm
